Happy Friday and welcome back to our 63rd Weekly Dose of Optimism.
Fall is upon us in NYC. It=E2=80=99s Q4 (for those who celebrate.) The Phil=
lies won their Wild Card Series and are moving onto the NLDS. The Eagles ar=
e 4-0. It=E2=80=99s Nobel Prize week.
Life is good.
Let=E2=80=99s get to it.
Instead of an ad, I want to tell you about=E2=80=A6 a16z Crypto Startup Sch=
ool [ https://substack.com/redirect/e1f17177-9030-427a-9b22-e182198768f5?j=
=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Packy here. a16z Crypto Startup School (CSS) is the premier web3 accelerato=
r program for early-stage companies, where founders can gain the expertise,=
 network, and capital they need to navigate this fast-paced industry. Over =
12 weeks, CSS teams will receive expert guidance to help develop their prod=
uct, level up go-to-market plans, and set their projects up for long-term s=
uccess.
Over the past couple of years, I=E2=80=99ve gotten to know the a16z crypto =
team well as an advisor, and I can=E2=80=99t recommend working with them hi=
ghly enough. They=E2=80=99re smart, thoughtful, curious, technical, and all=
 around good people. I=E2=80=99ve learned a ton from them. I also got to at=
tend CSS Demo Day in LA last year and can vouch for the exceptional talent =
CSS attracts. Do it.=20
The next CSS runs from March - June 2024 in London, and we=E2=80=99re looki=
ng for builders from around the globe who are intent on taking big, bold sw=
ings in crypto and web3. Applications are open to candidates worldwide thro=
ugh October 20th: =20
(1) WHO recommends malaria vaccine that will be rolled out next year [ http=
s://substack.com/redirect/852f287f-46e9-4a0b-aa0e-a83ff4877497?j=3DeyJ1Ijoi=
OXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Gabrielle T=C3=A9trault-Farber [ https://substack.com/redirect/2867c5d1-aa2=
6-46f7-8e33-ef37219b4061?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKb=
qOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] and Leroy Leo [ https://substack.com/redirect/a124399e-0=
7d4-4a5b-ba8b-83b4e0d4c614?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXep=
KbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] for Reuters
The World Health Organization (WHO) recommended on Monday the use of a seco=
nd malaria vaccine to curb the life-threatening disease spread to humans by=
 some mosquitoes.
We=E2=80=99re getting a second malaria vaccine, and this time we=E2=80=99re=
 getting it at scale.
Malaria kills 600,000 people per year, mostly children in Africa. It=E2=80=
=99s spread by mosquitoes, and once it gets into the body, it shape-shifts =
to hide from our immune systems. That makes it hard for our bodies to devel=
op immunity, and has presented a huge challenge to the scientists who have =
been trying to develop a vaccine for over a century.=20
Two years ago, the WHO recommended broad use of the world's first malaria v=
accine called RTS,S. The first ever approved malaria vaccine was a huge dea=
l, and if the Weekly Dose had been around, it would have been our headline =
story.=20
This newly recommended vaccine, R21/Matrix-M, shows similar efficacy as RTS=
,S but is also able to produced at scale. The world's largest vaccine manuf=
acturer - the Serum Institute of India - is already lined up to make more t=
han 100 million doses a year and plans to scale up to 200 million doses a y=
ear, and with scale comes lower costs. The vaccine will cost about half as =
much as RTS,S, and SII projects that supply will match demand for the new v=
accine in 2024.=20
Suck it, mosquitoes.=20
(2) 2023 Nobel Prize Winners Announced
Nobel Week baby! If there=E2=80=99s one week that reminds us that there are=
 some very smart, dedicated optimists out there pushing humanity forward, i=
t=E2=80=99s Nobel Week. Here=E2=80=99s a quick roundup of the winners.
All of the winners are wicked smart and impressive, but the story of the we=
ek is Katalin Karik=C3=B3, the UPenn researcher who=E2=80=99s been working =
on mRNA for nearly 35 years.=20
Karik=C3=B3 joined the University of Pennsylvania in 1989 on a tenure track=
 to work on mRNA, but struggled to get funding. By 1995, UPenn demoted her.=
 She bounced from lab to lab, before finally ending up in Drew Weissman=E2=
=80=99s lab. The two figured out a way to get the immune system to ignore m=
RNA in order to make it effective as a vaccine.=20
They still couldn=E2=80=99t get funding or publications =E2=80=94 the lifeb=
lood of academic research =E2=80=94 but Penn still filed patents on their w=
ork. When Karik=C3=B3 and Weissman spun out a company, RNARx, they couldn=
=E2=80=99t come to a licensing agreement with Penn. Instead, Penn sold the =
patents [ https://substack.com/redirect/6c1253b2-f1d8-4922-9a71-266a53c9362=
a?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] to a=
 small company for $300,000. When Moderna=E2=80=99s backers called Karik=C3=
=B3 to license the patents, she didn=E2=80=99t have them. They licensed fro=
m the company that bought them, Cellscript, instead. Moderna and BioNTech w=
ould end up paying out hundreds of millions of dollars to Cellscript for Ka=
rik=C3=B3 and Weissman=E2=80=99s work; meanwhile, RNARx shut down in 2013.=
=20
Karik=C3=B3 told a Nobel interviewer, =E2=80=9CI was kicked out from Penn, =
was forced to retire.=E2=80=9D=20
It=E2=80=99s thanks to her dogged determination in the face of a chilly rec=
eption from the academic community that we had mRNA vaccines when we needed=
 them during COVID. Her story begs the question: how many similarly brillia=
nt ideas have been lost because others just gave up?=20
How do we make sure the next Karik=C3=B3 doesn=E2=80=99t get lost in the sh=
uffle? Last October, Elliot Hershberg [ https://substack.com/redirect/aea9d=
c0e-a78e-49d9-aceb-47984d3f144b?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjm=
lXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] and Dr. Jocelynn Pearl [ https://substack.com/red=
irect/1f8c95f0-593c-46af-8447-9f74aca8bd50?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7Gn=
A_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] wrote a Not Boring piece, Gassing the =
Miracle Machine [ https://substack.com/redirect/3825e702-7ffe-4d57-bfa0-66d=
89ad7c661?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNp=
U ], on exactly that topic. It=E2=80=99s worth reading in light of Karik=C3=
=B3=E2=80=99s Nobel.=20
Here=E2=80=99s the full list of this year=E2=80=99s winners (economics is b=
eing announced Monday):
Physiology or Medicine:
Winners: Katalin Karik=C3=B3 and Drew Weissman
Achievement: Pioneering work on messenger RNA (mRNA), which directly paved =
the way for the creation of mRNA vaccines for Covid-19. According to some r=
eports [ https://substack.com/redirect/fd88a09a-f538-44f9-af4e-91d8b7ed4588=
?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], thes=
e vaccines saved 3 million lives, 18 million hospitalizations, and $1 Trill=
ion in the US alone.=20
Physics:
Winners: Pierre Agostini, Ferenc Krausz, and Anne L=E2=80=99Huillier
Achievement: Groundbreaking work on attosecond physics, allowing scientists=
 to capture the ultrafast motion of electrons. L=E2=80=99Huillier initiated=
 the understanding by studying light interactions at the electron level, wh=
ile Agostini and Krausz developed methods to produce incredibly short light=
 pulses, providing unprecedented insights into the dynamics of atomic and m=
olecular processes.
Chemistry:
Winners: Moungi G. Bawendi, Louis E. Brus, and Alexei I. Ekimov
Achievement: Recognized for the discovery and development of quantum dots. =
Quantum dots are semiconductor nanoparticles that have applications in vari=
ous areas, from medicine (like medical imaging) to technology (like quantum=
 dot displays in TVs).
Literature:
Winner: Jon Fosse from Norway
Achievement: Fosse's work is known for its minimalist style and deep explor=
ation of human psychology, emotions, and existential themes, which often to=
uch on topics that are hard to articulate.
Peace=20
Winner: Narges Mohammadi
Achievement: Mohammadi is an Irianian human rights activist and freedom fig=
hter. She=E2=80=99s been arrested 13 times, convicted five, and sentenced t=
o 31 years in prison and 154 lashes for fighting against the Iranian regime=
=E2=80=99s oppression of women. She=E2=80=99s currently in prison.=20
Humans rock. Especially Katalin Karik=C3=B3.=20
(3) Focused Ultrasound [ https://substack.com/redirect/bea9f3f5-a483-4f24-b=
da9-ab60afaee719?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m=
8ExkRNpU ]
From The Focused Ultrasound Foundation
This tweet from Steve Jurveston [ https://substack.com/redirect/0793bb96-88=
7b-4f1a-a973-dbcf0f72d122?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepK=
bqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] brought Focused Ultrasound (FUS) to our attention. Focu=
sed ultrasound utilizes ultrasonic energy to target tissue deep in the body=
 without the need for surgical incisions. Here=E2=80=99s how Jurveston summ=
ed it up, =E2=80=9CYou have probably seen ultrasound images of babies, but =
if you arrange an array of ultrasound transducers to focus to a point, they=
 can manipulate cells and membranes like a magnifying glass focusing sunlig=
ht to a burning hot point.=E2=80=9D It's a form of non-invasive therapy, an=
d while it=E2=80=99s still mostly in trial phases, its applications could r=
ange from tumor treatment to drug delivery.
At the same time, the technology does have some potential setbacks: impreci=
se targeting and overheating cells unintentionally. To be clear, we=E2=80=
=99re still early here and tons of more research is currently underway, but=
 the idea of using ultrasound to zap tumors is cool enough to include early=
=2E=20
There were no major announcements related to FUS this week (Jurveston tweet=
ed about it after apparently attending a conference on it) but it=E2=80=99s=
 not hard to imagine that the folks behind this technology could one day jo=
in the ranks of the Nobel winners we highlighted above.=20
(4) Poverty is back to pre-COVID levels globally, but not for low-income co=
untries. [ https://substack.com/redirect/6604069f-a54b-44bb-996c-49bbb85101=
a2?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
From The World Bank
The economic setbacks of the COVID-19 pandemic resulted in the largest incr=
ease in global extreme poverty in decades. Global poverty has now receded t=
o levels closer to those prior to the pandemic, but this means that we have=
 lost three years in the fight against poverty.=C2=A0 The recovery is also =
uneven: while extreme poverty in middle-income countries has decreased, pov=
erty in the poorest countries and countries affected by fragility, conflict=
 or violence is still worse than before the pandemic.=C2=A0
Good-ish news and bad news from the World Bank this week.
Good-ish news first: Global poverty levels have recovered since COVID setba=
cks. We=E2=80=99ve now reverted back to pre-pandemic levels.=20
Bad news: The poorest countries are still worse off than before the pandemi=
c.=20
Taken together, we=E2=80=99ve essentially lost 3 years of improving global =
poverty levels and during that time the most poor became poorer. That=E2=80=
=99s a pretty bleak story, but when you zoom out even just a few more years=
, the progress we=E2=80=99ve made on poverty is astounding.
Since 2011, extreme poverty rates have plummeted. Nearly 500  million peopl=
e worldwide have been lifted out of extreme poverty. Today about 9% of the =
world population lives on less than $2.15 per days; that % was nearly doubl=
e at the start of the 2010s.
A lot of work to be done. And certainly we=E2=80=99ll face pandemic-like se=
tbacks in the future. But if we extend that curve another decade, our bet/h=
ope is that another few hundred million folks will be lifted out of extreme=
 poverty. =20
(5) Towards Monosemanticity: Decomposing Language Models With Dictionary Le=
arning [ https://substack.com/redirect/a0019d04-463d-422a-8414-50d9d9d3398d=
?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
From Anthropic
Packy here. On Wednesday, I made a very funny joke about Google=E2=80=99s r=
umored investment in Anthropic at a $20-30 billion valuation [ https://subs=
tack.com/redirect/a841cd3d-224a-4d8e-af85-1d31e71ffab7?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Qi=
fQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]:
Yesterday, Anthropic responded by dropping a paper that demonstrates a big =
step towards understanding language models. As they tweeted [ https://subst=
ack.com/redirect/119c6aea-3dc8-4c36-8b92-7bac9213e965?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Qif=
Q.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], =E2=80=9CThe fact that mos=
t individual neurons are uninterpretable presents a serious roadblock to a =
mechanistic understanding of language models. We demonstrate a method for d=
ecomposing groups of neurons into interpretable features with the potential=
 to move past that roadblock.=E2=80=9D
I=E2=80=99m not smart enough to understand the paper, but according to peop=
le who are, Anthropic solved the hard problem of mechanic interpretability,=
 which might mean that we can make superintelligent AIs that won=E2=80=99t =
kill us.=20
Lesson learned: I won=E2=80=99t even make pessimistic jokes anymore.=20
Bigger lesson: there=E2=80=99s been so much hand-wringing about AI killing =
us all, and then humans just go out and turn mechanistic interpretability i=
nto a solvable engineering problem. That=E2=80=99s not to say =E2=80=9Cdon=
=E2=80=99t worry, everything will be fine.=E2=80=9D Anthropic was founded t=
o do research and build products that =E2=80=9Cput safety at the frontier.=
=E2=80=9D People have to do the work, but it keeps turning out that there a=
re no insoluble problems as long as you=E2=80=99re not trying to break the =
laws of physics.=20
Bonus: Boats, Boats, Boats
They say the two best days in a boat owner's life are the day they buy a bo=
at and the day they sell it. The same could probably be said of startup inv=
esting. Which makes this new wave of boat-tech startups particularly intere=
sting trend.
Arc [ https://substack.com/redirect/0e487cbd-7460-48c6-a2a6-7e44f05f7fb3?j=
=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]: The el=
ectric boat company raised a $70M Series B to commercialize its water-sport=
 vehicle. Beyond its low-noise, low-gas, and high performance characteristi=
cs, the EV boat it also better for the environment. Oh And it looks cool, t=
oo.
Navier [ https://substack.com/redirect/0ff46a89-b2a6-4c12-b935-ef0f8eb2d8a4=
?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]: And =
earlier this week, Jason Carman opened season two of his must-watch YouTube=
 series S=C2=B3 with a profile of Navier.
Navier=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9CN30=E2=80=9D hydrofoiling craft that is 10x more =
efficient than traditional gas powered boats, and has many of the same bene=
fits as Arc. Watch the video =E2=80=94 hydrofoilin=E2=80=99 e-boats are jus=
t fun to watch.
Regent [ https://substack.com/redirect/34f68a49-dff7-492b-9654-3bcb0aa1d9da=
?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]: The =
electric seaglider company just announced its $60M Series A lead by 8090 an=
d Founders Fund. The seaglider operates a few meters off the ground and cou=
ples the speed of airflight with the operational ease of boating. The plan =
is to use these craft to facilitate transportation between coastal cities.=
=20
And it just might be a step towards answering our favorite question: Where =
is My Flying Car? As Delian tweeted [ https://substack.com/redirect/4883582=
f-cc5a-4af2-a0c4-011c52d7807a?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlX=
XepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], =E2=80=9COur investment here is us continuing to d=
ouble down on the thesis that flying boats are the predecessor to flying ca=
rs.=E2=80=9D=20
The future of boating is bright. But I think that=E2=80=99s enough water ac=
tion for me today. Before I get seasick, let=E2=80=99s call it a newsletter=
=2E
That=E2=80=99s all for this week. If you have some time this weekend, check=
 out a16z Crypto Startup School. [ https://substack.com/redirect/4cc5b006-4=
730-480f-b1ce-9fe61f47f424?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXep=
KbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
We=E2=80=99ll be back in your inbox on Tuesday.
Thanks for reading,
Dan + Packy

